4 A BILL FOR AN ACT ENTITLED: “AN ACT ESTABLISHING AN INCOME TAX CREDIT TO OFFSET THE
5 COST OF A FIREARM SUPPRESSOR; PROVIDING THAT THE TAX CREDIT MAY BE CLAIMED AGAINST
6 ONLY THE COST OF A FEDERALLY REQUIRED PURCHASE OF A TAX STAMP; PROVIDING A
7 DEFINITION; AND PROVIDING A DELAYED EFFECTIVE DATE, AN APPLICABILITY DATE, AND A
8 TERMINATION DATE.”
9
10 WHEREAS, firearm suppressors or silencers are an effective means to combat widespread health
11 concerns for hunters and helps prevent shooters from long-term hearing damage; and
12 WHEREAS, the federal government mandates the purchase of firearm suppressor tax stamps for these
13 safety devices, which are already expensive; and
14 WHEREAS, the state of Montana has an opportunity to encourage citizen safety.
15
16 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF MONTANA:
17
18 NEW SECTION. Section 1. Firearm suppressor tax credit -- purpose. (1) There is a credit against
19 the tax imposed by this chapter to offset the cost of one firearm suppressor tax stamp purchased by a taxpayer.
20 (2) The credit allowed under this section must be claimed in the tax year in which a firearm
21 suppressor tax stamp is purchased, and the maximum amount of the credit is equal to the lesser of the cost for
22 the firearm suppressor tax stamp or $50 for each taxpayer claiming the credit.
23 (3) The credit must be refunded if the taxpayer has a tax liability less than the credit claimed.
24 (4) Pursuant to 5-4-104, the legislature finds that the purpose of the tax credit provided for in this
25 section is to protect shooters from long-term hearing damage by offsetting costs imposed by the federal
26 government for a safety device.
27 (5) As used in this section, "firearm suppressor tax stamp" means a stamp affixed to a federal
28 bureau of alcohol, tobacco, firearms and explosives form 1 or form 4 application to register a muffler or silencer.
